    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>But that is the beauty of cloaking the suspension in a "violation of team rules" and refusing to discuss it even three years later, right? Nobody will ever know whether rumors that the punishment did not fit the crime were true. People will continue to whisper over something that could have been put to rest with a little honesty.</p>
<p>If it were so important that whatever happened stay between Harding and her teammates and coaches, then Duke should have kept her accomplishments in the record books-not in Cameron's rafters.</p>
<p>In an e-mail late last week in response to my inquiry, President Brodhead wrote to me: "It's always pretty thrilling when these ceremonies take place; next week's will be as well."</p>
<p>Under these circumstances, I respectfully disagree.</p>

